College Majors - Who gets a job?

College students pursue their degrees, with little exception, hoping for a better chance at success. With half of young graduates in Petroleum Engineering earning $110k or more it is easy to imagine what a Petro Engineering major is pursuing. Even students dogged by How are you going to get a job with that? every Thanksgiving, however, are more likely than not seeking success in terms of a fulfilling life or a vibrant intellectual life.

But, vibrant intellectual life is hard to quantify and doesnt pay much rent. And, even if a Maserati isnt your idea of success, paying the rent probably should be. With that in mindand unemployed 20-somethings such a meme nowadayswell focus on some more bare-basics measures: Do young graduates in fields such as Arts, Education, Health, etc. have a job? Does it pay something livable?

Were focusing on US college graduates under 28 years-old. These data are estimates from fivethirtyeight.com, based on the American Community Survey 2010-2012 Public Use Microdata Series.

Unsurprisingly, the jobs new Arts grads find are more likely to be low paying than for new Engineers. But, low paying job is a very different matter than no job at all. Here, Education really leads the pack, and even the hard Sciences look to be laggards compared to those oft-mocked Artists. Each of these are good measures of job-market success, but they dont correlatea grain of salt the next time someone shares a USNews Highest paying majors listicle.

Another couple grains of salt: Those highest-salary figures say as much about who studies what as about how much they earn. Many women study in Education and Health fields. From the previous plot, we can see this as a prudent decision; graduates in either fields are unlikely to be left unemployed or in a low-paying job. You wont find either in one of those highest-salary listicles, however. With only 12% of majors in Petroleum Engineering (oh, that wellspring of human goodness!) being women, those salary figures should also make us question why were considering some labor, and laborers, worth paying so much less.
